<p>A. For each of the following sequences, decide whether or not the given sequence converges to a. limit.  If it does not converge to a limit, find in each case at least one convergent subsequence.  In what follows, we wuppose n=1, 2, 3, 4 ...

<ol>
  <li><m> x_n = (-1)^n ( 1- (1/n))</m></li>
  <li><m> x_n = (-1)^n ( 2- 2^{-1}))</m></li>
  <li><m> x_n = \sum_{j=1}^n (1/j!)</m></li>
  <li><m> x_n = (\sin(n \pi/3))(1-(1/n))</m></li>
  <li><m> x_n = 1+((-1)^n/n)</m></li>
  <li><m> x_n = \sum_{i=1}^n ((-1)^i/2^i)</m></li>
</ol></p>

<p>B.  The sequence <me> \{ 1 \frac{1}{2}, 2 \frac{1}{2}, 3 \frac{1}{2}, 1 \frac{1}{3}, 2 \frac{1}{3}, 3 \frac{1}{3}, 1 \frac{1}{4}, 2 \frac{1}{4}, 3 \frac{1}{4}, 1 \frac{1}{5}, 2 \frac{1}{5}, 3 \frac{1}{5}, \ldots \}</me> diverges because it has subsequences that converge to 1, 2, and 3.  Write a sequence which has subsequences that converge to <m>N</m> different numbers where <m>N</m> is any positive integer.</p>
</li>
